snippet.title: Pune Porsche Accident Case Update: Teen's Father Vishal Agarwal Sent To 2-Day Police Custody
snippet.description:
Pune Porsche Accident Case Update: Minor's Father Vishal Agarwal Sent To 2-Day Police Custody By Pune Court

 The father of the Pune teenager who rammed a Porsche into two techies, killing them on the spot, has been remanded in police custody for two days. The realtor had been arrested on Tuesday from Chhatrapati Sambhajinagar in Maharashtra, where he had allegedly gone to evade the cops. 

The pune porsche accident took place around 2.15 am on May 20, when the 17-year-old, who had been drinking with his friends in two pubs in Pune to celebrate his Class 12 results, knocked down the two 24-year-old IT professionals in the Kalyani Nagar area. Aneesh Awadhiya, who was riding the bike was sent flying and hit a parked car, while Ashwini Koshta - who was riding pillion - was flung 20 feet into the air. Both of them died on the spot. Advocate Asim Saraode has offered insights into the court's rationale for denying bail to the accused's father.

snippet.title: Pune Porsche Accident: Father Of Pune Teen, Who Killed 2 Techies, Arrested From Aurangabad | Pune
snippet.description:
Pune Porsche Accident: Father Of Pune Teen, Who Killed 2 Techies, Arrested From Aurangabad | Pune

Father of Pune teen, who killed 2 techies with Porsche, arrested from Aurangabad. The boy's father Vishal Agrawal was arrested from Maharashtra's Aurangabad after a case was registered against him on May 20. Vishal is a real estate developer he was detained from Chhatrapati Sambhajinagar area. Meanwhile, amid the uproar over bail granted to the teen, Police Commissioner Amitesh Kumar has stated that the 17-year-old should be treated as an adult. Talking to a media channel Kumar said 'we will not leave any stone unturned'.
"We have appealed against this order in a higher court yesterday. We will not leave any stone unturned to prove that this is a heinous crime."
Amitesh Kumar
Commissioner of Police, Pune

The teen is accused of running his Porsche over a couple who were on a two-wheeler in Kalyani Nagar area, Pune. The teen was allegedly under the influence of alcohol and was granted bail by a local court within 14 hours, citing that the crime was not 'serious' enough to deny bail.

snippet.title: Pune Porsche Accident: Victims' Parents Cry Bitterly, Demand Justice For Their Children
snippet.description:
Followed by the tragic Pune accident and ongoing investigation process, Anis Awadhiya’s family expressed grief over the tragic loss of Anis on May 21 in Madhya Pradesh’s Umaria. In the early hours of May 19, two individuals, Ashwini Koshta and Anis Awadhiya lost their lives after a luxury car collided with their motorcycle near Kalyani Nagar in Pune. 
Speaking to ANI, Anis’ mother Savita Soni expressed grief and said, “Somebody please give me back my son. He had no fault. His friends called at night and said Anis met with an accident and his condition is serious. He was doing job in Pune for the past two to three years. He was also financing his younger brother’s education; how will we manage everything now?
Speaking to ANI, Anis’ father Om Prakash Awadhia said, “He talked to his mother two days before the accident about his foreign trip for work. On the night of 19 May suddenly her mother’s phone rang and we got the news of his accident, we were asked to come to Pune immediately. How can we go to Pune all of a sudden? The car that caused the accident was worth crores of rupees. Police and government were not cooperative.”
Giving her reaction, Ashwini Koshta’s mother said, “First of all the parents should get punished for the upbringings that they are giving to their son. If anything like this doesn’t happen further law and police officials should investigate and take action. Our girl won’t come back. So we want no house has to go through something like this. On Sunday their son got bail within 4 hours when it is said that on Sunday everything remains shut. I just investigation to be carried out correctly.”

snippet.description:
Tragic Incident: Early Sunday morning, two IT professionals, Anis Awadhiya and Ashwini Costa, were killed in Pune's Kalyani Nagar when a Porsche, allegedly driven by an intoxicated minor, crashed into their motorbike. The minor was granted bail shortly after, with conditions to work with the Yerwada traffic police for 15 days and write an essay on road accidents.

Public Outrage: Maharashtra Deputy Chief Minister Devendra Fadnavis expressed shock over the Juvenile Justice Board's lenient decision. Despite police petitions to try the 17-year-old as an adult, the board released him on bail, prompting police to seek higher court intervention.

Families Demand Justice: The families of the victims are devastated and demanding justice. Ashwini, from Jabalpur, had planned to surprise her father on his birthday. Anis, from Pali, had been working in Pune after graduating from DY Patil College of Engineering. Both families are calling for stricter measures against such crimes.

snippet.description: A fatal accident occurred in Quepem on Sunday night, where a car crashed into three scooter riders. Abdul Khader Badshah, one of the scooter riders, died instantly, while another rider, Sufyan Shaikh, sustained critical injuries. The driver of the car fled the scene after the incident. Locals reportedly discovered packets of a green leafy substance, suspected to be narcotics, inside the car. The police, along with a forensic team, conducted a panchnama and seized the vehicle.

snippet.title: National Highway 66 at Malpe Pernem has been become a death spot
snippet.description: The condition of the National Highway at MalpemPernem is so bad that it has virtually turned into a death spot. There is heavy traffic of trucks, buses and other interstate vehicles on this road. The new highway has been closed for the last four months due to collapse of the protection wall which has not been repaired and traffic is diverted via the old highway. In the past two weeks at least three vehicles including containers have overturned on this highway due to the potholes.
